1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,500
Physicians spend 12 hours per week
on prior authorizations.

2
00:00:03,500 --> 00:00:07,000
That's 43 requests per physician,
costing the healthcare system

3
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:10,000
31 billion dollars annually.

4
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:13,000
The problem? Clinical data is locked
in fragmented EHR systems,

5
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:17,000
and payers require extensive documentation
in formats physicians don't have time to prepare.

6
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:23,000
AuthClear solves this with two AI agents:

7
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:25,500
a FHIR terminology engine

8
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:28,000
and a prior authorization copilot.

9
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Let me show you how it works.

10
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:33,500
AuthClear consists of two agents.
First, the MCP Server:

11
00:00:33,500 --> 00:00:38,000
a clinical terminology engine that translates
ICD-10, RxNorm, and LOINC codes

12
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:40,000
using FHIR R4 standards.

13
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:43,000
Second, the A2A Agent:

14
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:46,000
a prior authorization copilot that reads
patient data,

15
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:50,000
identifies requirements, and generates
structured authorization drafts.

16
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Let's start with the MCP Server.

17
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:56,500
I'm resolving ICD-10 code E11.9 -
Type 2 Diabetes.

18
00:00:56,500 --> 00:01:00,000
The server translates it to SNOMED code 44054006

19
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,000
and provides the clinical description.

20
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Next, I look up the drug Ozempic.

21
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:08,500
The server returns the RxNorm ID,
drug class GLP-1 receptor agonist,

22
00:01:08,500 --> 00:01:10,500
and confirms it requires prior authorization.

23
00:01:10,500 --> 00:01:15,000
Finally, I retrieve the prior auth criteria
for semaglutide from a generic payer.

24
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:18,500
The server returns required diagnoses,
lab thresholds,

25
00:01:18,500 --> 00:01:20,500
and medication trial requirements.

26
00:01:20,500 --> 00:01:24,000
All of this happens in milliseconds
using hardcoded mappings for common codes,

27
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:26,500
with API fallback for rare cases.

28
00:01:26,500 --> 00:01:30,000
The MCP Server is now ready
to serve the A2A Agent.

29
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Now the A2A Agent.

30
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:36,500
I'm loading a synthetic FHIR bundle
for Maria González,

31
00:01:36,500 --> 00:01:39,000
a 50-year-old patient with Type 2 Diabetes.

32
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:42,500
She has an HbA1c of 8.9%, BMI of 34,

33
00:01:42,500 --> 00:01:45,000
and has tried Metformin and Glipizide
for over 3 months.

34
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:48,000
The agent parses the FHIR bundle,

35
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:52,000
extracts 1 diagnosis, 2 medications,
and 2 lab results.

36
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:56,000
It then calls the MCP Server to resolve
all clinical codes

37
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,000
and retrieve prior auth criteria for Ozempic.

38
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:03,500
Using Claude's reasoning, the agent analyzes
whether Maria meets the criteria:

39
00:02:03,500 --> 00:02:06,000
HbA1c above 7.5? Yes.

40
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:08,000
BMI above 30? Yes.

41
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,500
Two oral agents tried? Yes.

42
00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:12,000
All criteria met.

43
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:16,500
The agent generates a structured
prior authorization draft with 90% confidence,

44
00:02:16,500 --> 00:02:19,000
clinical justification, and supporting evidence.

45
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:22,500
Most importantly, it flags this
for human review -

46
00:02:22,500 --> 00:02:25,000
we never auto-approve.

47
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:30,000
AuthClear is compliant with state
AI transparency laws:

48
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Texas SB 490, Arizona HB 2417,
and Maryland HB 1174.

49
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:40,000
Human-in-the-loop is architecturally enforced -
no agent can approve or deny authorizations.

50
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:43,000
The impact? For a 10-physician practice

51
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,000
processing 430 prior auths per week,

52
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:50,000
AuthClear saves 8 hours per week
in staff time.

53
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:53,500
That's $83,000 per year in labor costs alone.

54
00:02:53,500 --> 00:02:55,000
AuthClear:

55
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:59,000
AI-powered prior authorization
that keeps physicians in control.
